Â–Aurangabad, located in Maharashtra, India, has a rich historical significance dating back to ancient times. Initially known as "Khadki," the city gained prominence during the reign of the Mughal Empire. It was named after the Mughal Emperor Aurangzeb, who made it his base of operations in the 17th century. Under Aurangzeb's rule, it became a key administrative center and military stronghold. The city is renowned for its architectural heritage, including the Bibi Ka Maqbara, often referred to as the "Taj of the Deccan," built in memory of his wife, Dilras Banu Begum. Aurangabad is also close to significant historical sites like the Ajanta and Ellora Caves, both UNESCO World Heritage Sites known for their ancient Buddhist, Hindu, and Jain rock-cut temples and monasteries. The region was part of several important empires, including the Rashtrakuta, Yadava, and Nizam dynasties, before coming under British rule in the 19th century. The city continues to be an important cultural and historical hub in Maharashtra, reflecting its diverse heritage from ancient to modern times.
